$QCOM to oversimplify the situation. QCOM bought Nuvia which had a license with $ARM. They believe the Nuvia license is transferrable to QCOM because they now own the company but ARM says it doesn't and they want the license theyll have to buy it. The amount the want is much more because of QCOMs size. I imagine QCOM tried to pass the extra cost of aquiring the license  to $AAPL who said they won't pay. It's contract law. Does the original license agreement with Nuvia include a clause that says what happens if the company is purchased by another. If it doesn't (the fact that are going to court suggests not) then the contract with Nuvia stays the same. The only way I can see $ARM winning is if when they acquired Nu they dissolved the old company and created a new entity.

Jay 44.52% in GLLC, Apple 20%, Ins 18%, Retail 18%
